<exercise id="eip-id1169190623482" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="eip-id1169180473855">
     <para id="import-auto-id2392409">On a trip, you notice that a 3.50-kg bag of ice lasts an average of one day in your cooler. What is the average power in watts entering the ice if it starts at <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>0º</m:mn><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{0°C} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and completely melts to <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>0º</m:mn><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math> water in exactly one day <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi/><m:mtext>1 watt = 1 joule/second</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo stretchy="false"> (</m:mo><m:mtext>1 W = 1 J/s</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math>?</para></problem>
            <solution id="fs-id2400878" type="problems-exercises">
